Model can make wrong predictions as:¶

  1. Predicting a customer will churn but actually the customer will not churn.
  2. Predicting a customer will not churn but actually, the customer will churn.

Which wrong prediction is more important for us ?

  • The option 2 because even if we predict that the non-churned customer will churn then the company will bear only a negligible loss related to contacting him/she for a churning prevention. The loss from non-identified churn customers would be much higher as after their leaving the company will loose payments which the customer paid each time.

Since we don't want people to churn we should use Recall as a metric of model evaluation instead of accuracy or precision.

  • Recall gives the ratio of True positives to Actual positives, so high Recall implies minimizing the costs from churning

  • The share of churned customers is 26% i.e. the share of non-churned customers is 74% (as similar as the accuracy of our basic model on test set). This means that if we would predict that nobody would churn then our prediction would be true during 74 % of time. Therefore, our basic model with 74% accuracy shows the same performance as a dummy strategy. Hence, the accuracy of 74% is actually quite bad performance (due to overfitting). Therefore, let us build other model of decision trees

First, let's create functions to calculate different metrics and confusion matrix so that we don't have to use the same code repeatedly for each model.¶

  • The model_performance_classification_sklearn function will be used to check the model performance of models.
  • The confusion_matrix_sklearnfunction will be used to plot the confusion matrix.
In [14]:
# defining a function to compute different metrics to check performance of a classification model built using sklearn
def model_performance_classification_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check classification model performance

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target, pred)  # to compute Recall
    precision = precision_score(target, pred)  # to compute Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred)  # to compute F1-score

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {"Accuracy": acc, "Recall": recall, "Precision": precision, "F1": f1,},
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf
In [15]:
def confusion_matrix_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    To plot the confusion_matrix with percentages

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """
    y_pred = model.predict(predictors)
    cm = confusion_matrix(target, y_pred)
    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ["{0:0.0f}".format(item) + "\n{0:.2%}".format(item / cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(2, 2)

    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt="")
    plt.ylabel("True label")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")

Apply different pruning techniques and check the model performance¶

In [21]:
# Choose the type of classifier.
estimator = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=1)

# Grid of parameters to choose from

parameters = {
    "max_depth": [np.arange(2, 50, 5), None],
    "criterion": ["entropy", "gini"],
    "splitter": ["best", "random"],
    "min_impurity_decrease": [0.000001, 0.00001, 0.0001],
    "max_leaf_nodes" : [1, 2, 5, 7, 10,15,20,50],
    "min_samples_leaf": [1, 2, 5, 7, 10,15,20]
}
              
# Type of scoring used to compare parameter combinations
acc_scorer = make_scorer(recall_score)

# Run the grid search
grid_obj = GridSearchCV(estimator, parameters, scoring=acc_scorer, cv=5)
grid_obj = grid_obj.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Set the clf to the best combination of parameters
estimator = grid_obj.best_estimator_

# Fit the best algorithm to the data.
estimator.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Next, we train a decision tree using the effective alphas. 
clfs = []
for ccp_alpha in ccp_alphas:
    clf = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=1, ccp_alpha=ccp_alpha)
    clf.fit(X_train, y_train)
    clfs.append(clf)
print(
    "Number of nodes in the last tree is: {} with ccp_alpha: {}".format(
        clfs[-1].tree_.node_count, ccp_alphas[-1]
    )
)

Number of nodes in the last tree is: 1 with ccp_alpha: 0.061566926377471354

Conclusions¶

Our best model (after a pre-pruning) can predict 64 % of churned customers! According to the best model, the most important factors : month-to-month contracts, internet service fiber optic, tenure and charges. This means that these factors should be furher investigated to understand the reasons of churning.

Recommendations¶

  • Check the terms of month-to-month contracts, internet service fiber optic, and charges against our comeptitors as it seems that these factors contribute to churning.

  • Performance of model remains quite moderate - only 64 % of churned customers are identified (while a precision is 60%). Therefore, the prediction of churned customers should be further improved. For this purpose, several measures can be taken:

    • other ML models may be considered together with their calibration (hyperparameter tunning). Their perforamnce should be compared with our best model and if neccesary the model should be changed.
    • Adding new features into the dataframe may probably improve the prediction. These new features may be related to financial issues (as this is important factor per our models)or any other parameters decsribing the churned customers. For better undestanding the profile of churned customers, unsupevised clustering may be perfomed. From cluster with high number of churned customers, we may deduce insignts on new features which may be incorporated in a dataframe.
    • Post analysis of our best model may probably allow us to suggest a heuristic technique which may further improve the prediction of our model. For instance, we may say that if model predicts that the customer will not churn but if some parameter "X" (to be defined) is true then we assume that this person will churn. This would allow us increase the number of prediction when a customer is marked as a churn and therefore it should increase the recall value.
